===Etymology 1===
Middle Chinese distinguishes {{ltc-l|推|to push|id=2}} and {{ltc-l|推|to proceed; to promote; to deduce|id=1}}.

Older Mandarin dictionaries{{ref|group=n|name=n1|Samuel Wells Williams, 1874; Herbert Allen Giles, 1892}} give ''chuī'' (the Mandarin reflex of {{ltc-l|推||id=1}}) as a variant reading for all senses, while Cantonese dictionaries{{ref|group=n|name=n2|John Chalmers, 1855; Samuel Wells Williams, 1856; 廣話國語一貫未定稿, 1916}} only assign ''ceoi1'' to the "to deduce" sense (e.g. in {{zh-l|*推測|-|to surmise}}). Most modern Sinitic varieties use the reflexes of {{ltc-l|推||id=2}} for all meanings, while Sino-Xenic use the reflexes of {{ltc-l|推||id=1}} (in Korean, however, the reflex of {{ltc-l|推||id=2}} is also used in a few words). Some varieties (including certain Hakka, Min, and sometimes Yue dialects) preserve both readings, but not necessarily disambiguate them by meaning.

Outside of Sinitic, {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} adduces {{cog|cdm|दुस्|t=to push away, shove}} as a cognate. Note also similarities to {{cog|my|တိုး|t=to push, shove, advance}}.

See also {{ltc-l|揣}}.

